\section{Introduction}\label{thesis_introductions}
{\LARGE T}he horn antenna invented by J. C. Bose \cite{Emerson_work_of_Jagadis_Chandra_Bose} in the 1890\rq s is a good canonical problem as it has a broad range of low response in the backward (LRB) directions \cite{Katz_FDTD_Analysis_Horn_Antennas}. Keller\rq s geometrical theory of diffraction (GTD) and parallel plate waveguide mode approximation was used by Yu $et~al.$ to obtain the H-plane pattern in \cite{Rudduck_hp_horn}. The GTD prediction was in good agreement with measurements in the forward direction. In the back lobe direction it was shown that the E-edge contributions were significant for observation angle $\theta$ at and around $180^\circ$. However, there remained wide differences in LRB region. For $\theta> 105^\circ$, better result in the average was obtained by taking into account the finite edge effect of the E-edges using current elements. The dip at $180^\circ$ was conjectured to be caused by the detector mount used. These works were later followed by those of Mentzer $et~al.$ who used the extended equivalent current concept \cite{Mentzer_s_diff}. The finitedifference time-domain (FDTD) technique was applied by Taflove and Umashankar \cite{Katz_FDTD_Analysis_Horn_Antennas} and later Tirkas and Balanis \cite{Balanis_Finite-difference_time-domain_antenna_radiation} to the horn radiation problem and results obtained for small aperture horns.


In this work the formulation given in \cite{Rudduck_hp_horn} for H-plane horn radiation is reconsidered with spherical source excitation and in conjunction with corner diffraction to provide a GTD model of the uniform theory of diffraction (UTD) type \cite{Pathak_utd} and which takes into account the finiteness of the horn edges. A new heuristic corner slope diffraction (CSD) coefficient is presented. Addition of the CSD terms is found to provide further refinement to the GTD model. The finite edge GTD predicted results are compared with available measured and earlier predictions. In addition, the FDTD technique is used to obtain the H-plane horn radiation pattern and results compared with measurements and finite edge GTD prediction.
