Application of the geometrical theory of diffraction (GTD) to predict accurately the far out sidelobes and backlobe of a pyramidal horn antenna in the E-plane has been a subject of interest for quite sometime. Keller\rq s GTD \cite{Keller_gtd} and later the uniform theory of diffraction (UTD) \cite{Pathak_utd} and the uniform asymptotic theory (UAT) \cite{Boersma_uat}, \cite{Lee_uat_curved_wedge} have been applied to horn antennas \cite{Yu_Rudduck_E_plane}, \cite{Narsimhan_GTD_analysis_pyramidal_horns}. In \cite{Sanyal_Bhatt_E-plane_horn}, Sanyal and Bhattacharyya applied UAT using the magnetic line source at the vertex of a dihedral corner reflector to obtain the E-plane horn radiations. The higher order fields were computed using image principle \cite{Yu_Rudduck_E_plane} and multiply diffracted rays. The effect of corner diffractions if any on the E-plane pattern remains to be determined. The problem of horn radiation in the diagonal plane is also of interest to validate the corner diffraction coefficient. 


In the radiation and scattering problems where electrically large structures are involved, efficient solution is provided by GTD, UTD or UAT. Due to the local nature of diffraction at high frequencies, GTD analysis can be developed by, simulating these structures with components having shapes that locally provide a sufficiently accurate representation of the dominant reflection and diffraction effects. The analysis of a complex scatterer is usually carried out by breaking the problem into simpler problems involving canonical structures like half-plane, corner, cone etc.



Application of GTD to predict the radar cross section (RCS) has been a subject of interest for quite some time. Ross \cite{Ross_RCS_rectangular_flat_plates} applied Keller\rq s GTD \cite{Keller_gtd} to the problem of monostatic scattering by perfectly conducting plates. Plonus, Williams, and Wang \cite{Plonus_RCS_curved_plates_PTD} formulated the problem of monostatic scattering by a finite cylindrically curved plate using GO, PO, GTD and PTD. Sanyal and Bhattacharyya applied the UAT \cite{S_Sanyal_thesis}, \cite{Sanyal_Bhatt_curved_plate} to obtain the field scattered by the curved plate. We note that the GTD (and its extensions the UTD, UAT) predictions give two-dimensional $(2 -D)$ scattered fields. Therefore, a $2-D$ to three-dimensional $(3 -D)$ field conversion based on PO was necessary in \cite{Yu_Rudduck_E_plane}, \cite{Plonus_RCS_curved_plates_PTD}, \cite{Sanyal_Bhatt_curved_plate} to obtain the RCS. The problem of mono-static scattering by a triangular-plate has earlier been formulated by Sikta \cite{Sikta_PhD_Thesis}. Sikta calculated the fields using Ryan and Peters equivalent currents \cite{Ryan_Evaluation_edge_diffracted_fields_equivalent_currents} to find the first order terms plus higher order (double and triple) diffraction terms. However, to the best of the author\rq s knowledge, no GTD formulations of scattering by Sikta\rq s triangle is available till date. RCS of finite structures being a $3-D$ concept, it is of interest to test finite edge GTD predictions of the scattered field from a finite scatterer like the Sikta\rq s triangle with measurements \cite{Brinkley_UTD_Higher_Order_Terms} and other techniques \cite{Ivrissimtzis_uniform_ray_higher_order_terms} including FDTD technique.

